<div class="container">
  <div class="page-head">
    <h1>Features</h1>
    <p class="lede">Cueport reads your Serato library, lets you edit on your own terms in a local working layer, and pushes changes back when you ask. The release notes below cover what is in the current build.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="feature-list">
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Serato library reader</h3>
      <p>Cueport reads crates, subcrates, tracks, BPM, key, and color labels straight from your <code>_Serato_</code> folder on disk.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Cue points and track notes</h3>
      <p>Cueport reads hot cues from each MP3's Serato Markers and uses the Comment field as the track note.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Local editing layer</h3>
      <p>Cueport stages your cue point edits, note changes, and new collections in a local database with a clear sync status on every entity.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Publish on your terms</h3>
      <p>Cueport writes your staged edits back to your Serato MP3s and crate files only when you choose to publish. Until then, Serato stays untouched.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Local audio playback</h3>
      <p>Cueport plays tracks from your local files alongside the waveform, beatgrid, and your hot cues, so you can audition without leaving the library.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Backups and restore points</h3>
      <p>Cueport duplicates <code>_Serato_</code> into Application Support after you link it and takes a restore point before every publish so any push can be rolled back.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>
